{"questionId":"2601249","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the following diagram, which shows the plan of part of a house.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong>diagram not to scale</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/3243ec9316c8c564e032351d69963dffb7ce242b.png\"></p>\n<p>A narrow passageway with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> width is perpendicular to a room of width <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>. There is a corner at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>. Points&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> are variable points on the base of the walls such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> lie on a straight line.</p>\n<p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> denote the length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AB</mi></math> in metres.</p>\n<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi></math> be the angle that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>AB</mi><mo>]</mo></math> makes with the room wall, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>α</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>arctan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math>, show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mi>α</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to find a ratio other than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi></math> using an appropriate trigonometric identity OR a right triangle with at least two side lengths seen&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;Award&nbsp;<em><strong>M0</strong></em>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>arctan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;substituted into their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mi>α</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;with no further progress.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>one correct ratio&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sec</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cosec</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cot</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;<em><strong>M1A1</strong>&nbsp;</em>may be seen in part (d).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mfenced><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mfenced><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mfenced><mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A2</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>12</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>15</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>15</mn><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;Award&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em>&nbsp;for only two or three correct terms.</p>\n<p>Award a maximum of&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)(A1)A1</strong></em>&nbsp;on&nbsp;<em><strong>FT</strong></em>&nbsp;from c(i).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>L</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mi>α</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><mn>45</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><msqrt><mn>5</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2601249","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ1.11cii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"When α=arctan 2, show that d2Ldα2=4545.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.7—The second derivative","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.8—Testing for max and min, optimisation. Points of inflexion","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.15—Further derivatives and indefinite integration of these, partial fractions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Reciprocal trig ratios and their pythagorean identities. Inverse circular functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
